'''SingleMuslim.com''' is a [[matrimonial website]] designed for and marketed to [[Muslim]]s. The website was launched on 1 August 2000, and its headquarters are is based in [[Wakefield]], [[West Yorkshire]], [[England]].

==History==
Founder and managing director Adeem Younis conceived the idea for SingleMuslim.com<ref name="theasiantoday">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.theasiantoday.com/article.aspx?articleId=2130|title=Marriage made on the Net|work= |location= |publisher=''[[The Asian Today]]''|date=10 August 2010|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref><ref name="desixpress">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.desixpress.co.uk/PrintArticle.aspx?articleID=2130|title=Marriage made on the Net|work= |location= |publisher=''[[Desi Xpress]]''|date=10 August 2010|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> when he was a 19 year old undergraduate student at the [[University of Leeds]].<ref name="biyokulule">{{cite news |last=de Muth|first=Susan|url=http://www.biyokulule.com/view_content.php?articleid=5590|title=Muslim matrimonial websites--halal or haram?|work= |location= |publisher=''[[The Middle East (magazine)|The Middle East]]''|date=1 January 2011|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref><ref name="patheos">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.patheos.com/blogs/mmw/2011/11/whos-behind-online-dating-and-why-does-it-matter/|title=Who<U+2019>s Behind Online Dating, and Why Does it Matter?|work= |location= |publisher=''Patheos''|date=30 November 2011|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> On 1 August 2000, Younis launched the website from his office, above a fast food shop in [[Wakefield]], [[West Yorkshire]], [[England]]. Friends and contacts in the local community helped the venture by offering support with website development, photography, and other essentials.<ref name="theasiantoday"/><ref name="desixpress"/>

The company has grown from just two original members of staff to eight and expects to keep expanding as the website continues to grow internationally.<ref name="marycreagh">{{cite web |url=http://www.marycreagh.co.uk/?id=954|title=Wakefield business talent wins national award in Parliament|publisher=Mary Creagh|date= |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> As well as being available in the United Kingdom, the website also has Pakistani-, Canadian-, Australian-, and American-centered web pages.<ref name="abcnews">{{cite news |last=Lee|first=Rebecca|url=http://abcnews.go.com/WN/Technology/story?id=3223316&page=1#.UVIl8lckRbA|title=MDate Joins Ranks of Faith-Based Matchmaking Web Sites|work= |location= |publisher=''[[ABC News]]''|date=29 May 2007|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

SingleMuslim.com also works in partnership with Muslim Marriage Events. In 2010, 130,000 members signed up to their events in the United Kingdom.<ref name="thenational1">{{cite news |last=Murtagh|first=Mary|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/world/europe/muslims-in-the-uk-try-a-western-approach-to-matchmaking#page4|title=Muslims in the UK try a western approach to matchmaking|work= |location= |publisher=''[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]''|date=8 February 2011|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

==Features==
SingleMuslim.com works as an introductions agency to help single Muslims find a compatible marriage partner, as an alternative to using traditional methods.<ref name="yorkshireeveningpost">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/latest-news/top-stories/love-digital-dating-1-3086426|title= Love: Digital dating|work= |location= |publisher=''[[Yorkshire Evening Post]]''|date=14 February 2011|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> Gold Membership entitles users full access to all the services offered by the website. Women are offered Gold Membership free of charge, whereas men are required to pay for Gold Membership packages on a reoccurring subscription.<ref name="singlemuslim1">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://uk.singlemuslim.com/help.php?cID=9|title=Membership Packages|work= |location= |publisher=''SingleMuslim.com''|date= |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

The website allows users to create a profile with personal, faith-based, educational, and professional information, and upload pictures. Users can send instant messages to members of the opposite gender, and send them virtual gifts. Users can perform searches of the member database based on criteria such as age, religious sect, location, country of origin, piety, citizenship, language(s), marital status, education, and profession. The website also has a real time live chat feature.

The website team manually vet each profile data and photographs for authenticity.<ref name="theasiantoday"/><ref name="desixpress"/><ref name="realbusiness">{{cite news |last=Hancock|first=Melisaa|url=http://realbusiness.co.uk/article/708-matchmaking_the_muslim_way|title=Matchmaking the Muslim way|work= |location= |publisher=''Real Business''|date=1 April 2008|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> The website is also self-regulating so users can report other users who are misusing the service, or who may not be genuine users, and there is a zero-tolerance policy in place where such people will be removed. Family or friends can also register on the website on behalf of someone.<ref name="realbusiness"/>

==Statistics==
By the end of 2002, SingleMuslim.com had over 10,000 registered users registered.<ref name="theasiantoday"/><ref name="desixpress"/> By June 2005, there were over 50,000 active accounts on the website, and in December 2006 the website had its 100,000th user. The website has over 14,000 new members joining the website every month and an increasing number of international members are being drawn to the website.<ref name="realbusiness">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://realbusiness.co.uk/article/708-matchmaking_the_muslim_way|title=Matchmaking the Muslim way|work= |location= |publisher=''Real Business''|date=1 April 2008|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> As of August 2010, there were over registered 500,000 members, which rose to 600,000 members in January 2011. More than 500 new user accounts are registered every day. In October 2012, the website had its millionth user.<ref name="theasiantoday"/><ref name="desixpress"/><ref name="biyokulule"/> Since 2004, the website has seen a 1,000 percent growth in users and a tenfold increase in turnover.<ref name="realbusiness"/>

Since 2007, SingleMuslim.com has learned of an average of four new marriages every day. The website is thought to have brought around 10,000 marriages.<ref name="theasiantoday"/><ref name="desixpress"/> On average two people a day leave the website having found success.<ref name="weeklyzaman">{{cite news |last=Turner|first=Hossein|url=http://www.weeklyzaman.com/en/newsDetail_getNewsById.action?newsId=5471|title=Is there a marriage crisis in the British Muslim community?|work= |location=Durham|publisher=''Weekly Zaman''|date=7 January 2012|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

Around half of the website<U+2019>s users are [[British Muslims]],<ref name="datingsitesreviews">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.datingsitesreviews.com/article.php?story=Online-Dating-Trends-Muslim-Dating|title=Online Dating Trends: A Look At The Popularity Of Muslim Dating|work= |location= |publisher=''Dating Sites Reviews''|date=4 January 2011|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>{{verify credibility|date=April 2014}} therefore 10 percent of the UK<U+2019>s 2.4 million Muslims are registered with SingleMuslim.com, and on average the website receives over 40,000 unique visits every day.<ref name="theasiantoday"/><ref name="desixpress"/>

There is a 2:1 ratio of men to women using the website, which may reflect some of the cultural perceptions of using the Internet to find a marriage partner. The ratio of men to women using the website used to be 6:1, however the number of women registering has increased since free Gold Membership was introduced to women.<ref name="theasiantoday"/><ref name="desixpress"/>

==Surveys==
In July 2009, a survey revealed that an overwhelming majority of Muslims believe that, ideally, Muslims should be married by the age of 25.<ref name="asianimage">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.asianimage.co.uk/news/4491210.Twenty_five_is_ideal_marriage_age_says_survey/|title=Twenty-five is ideal marriage age says survey|work= |location= |publisher=''Asian Image''|date=14 July 2009|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

In February 2010, a survey found that Muslim couples were scaling back their wedding celebrations.<ref name="middle-east2">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=36960|title=Recession hits Muslim wedding plans|work= |location= |publisher=''Middle East Online''|date=1 February 2010|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

In May 2010, A survey revealed that most Muslims who stated a preference believe pre-marital health screening is essential.<ref name="middle-east4">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=38877|title=Muslims believe pre-marital health checks to be 'essential'|work= |location= |publisher=''Middle East Online''|date=7 May 2010|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref><ref name="siasat">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.siasat.com/english/news/muslims-believe-pre-marital-health-checks-be-essential|title=Muslims believe pre-marital health checks to be 'essential'|work= |location= |publisher=''[[The Siasat Daily]]''|date=7 May 2010|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

In June 2010, a survey showed that when asked to state a preference, over one third of the website<U+2019>s users look primarily for evidence of piety and religious compatibly when looking for an ideal marriage partner.<ref name="middle-east3">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=39742|title=Piety tops marriage criteria among Muslims|work= |location= |publisher=''Middle East Online''|date=24 June 2010|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref><ref name="canoe">{{cite news |last= |first=Reuters|url=http://lifewise.canoe.ca/SexRomance/2010/06/24/14499016.html|title=Muslims look for piety first in partners: poll|work= |location= |publisher=''Canoe''|date=24 June 2010|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

In October 2010, a survey revealed that a majority of the Muslims believe that they would personally not choose to practise polygamy given the choice.<ref name="tribune">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/72451/majority-of-muslims-not-for-polygamy-poll/|title=Majority of Muslims not for polygamy: Poll|work= |location= |publisher=''[[The Express Tribune]]''|date=4 November 2010|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref><ref name="islamonline">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://islamonline.com/news/articles/2/Survey-reveals-Muslim-attitudes-to-polygamy.html|title=Survey reveals Muslim attitudes to polygamy|work= |location= |publisher=''Islam Online''|date=29 October 2010|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

In January 2011, A survey showed that Muslims (particularly Muslim women) prefer to marry closer to home.<ref name="islamonline">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://islamonline.com/news/articles/2/Survey-reveals-Muslim-attitudes-to-polygamy.html|title=Home town is where the heart is for Muslim women|work= |location= |publisher=''Islam Online''|date=11 January 2011|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref><ref name="middle-east5">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=43517|title=Home town is where the heart is for Muslim women|work= |location= |publisher=''Middle East Online''|date=7 January 2011|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> The survey concluded that more than 65 percent of members would prefer their ideal marriage partner to come from the same country as them. A third of those polled would prefer their future spouse to come from the same town or city.<ref name="republika">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.republika.co.id/berita/dunia-islam/islam-mancanegara/11/01/24/160292-apa-sih-yang-ada-di-benak-muslimah-inggris-tentang-jodoh-mereka-|title=What British Muslim's think about their love-match?|work= |location= |publisher=''Republika''|date=24 January 2011|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

In February 2011, a survey showed that the majority of Muslim men would prefer to marry someone younger.<ref name="middle-east6">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=44091|title=Muslim women seek older husbands|work= |location= |publisher=''Middle East Online''|date=4 February 2011|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

==Media and reception==
On 3 October 2007, [[BBC One]] broadcast a documentary about SingleMuslim.com entitled ''Single British Muslims.com''.<ref name="realbusiness">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://realbusiness.co.uk/article/708-matchmaking_the_muslim_way|title=Matchmaking the Muslim way|work= |location= |publisher=''Real Business''|date=1 April 2008|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref><ref name="charliegillett">{{cite news |last= |first=Charlie|url=http://www.charliegillett.com/bb/viewtopic.php?f=62&t=5314|title=Single Muslim - BBC One, 3rd October, 23.320|work= |location= |publisher=''Charlie Gillett''|date=2 October 2007|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> In August 2008, the website featured on a two episodes of six-part [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV1]] series, ''A Match Made in Heaven''.<ref name="edge">{{cite web |url=http://www.edge.co.uk/success-stories/adeem-younis|title=Adeem Younis|publisher=Edge Foundation|date= |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref><ref name="singlemuslim2">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://uk.singlemuslim.com/news_artical.php?aID=1774|title=A Match Made In Heaven, ITV1, July 13 - Aug 17|work= |location= |publisher=''SingleMuslim.com''|date=17 August 2009|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

In June 2009, [[Majid Nagra]], candidate from [[The Apprentice (UK series five)|series five]] of BBC reality television programme ''[[The Apprentice (UK)|The Apprentice]]'', endorsed the website.<ref name="singlemuslim1">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.singlemuslim.com/news_artical.php?aID=3131|title=The Apprentice star Majid backs SingleMuslim.com|work= |location= |publisher=''SingleMuslim.com''|date=9 June 2009|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

In August 2010, [[Catherine Heseltine]], [[Muslim Public Affairs Committee UK]] (MPACUK) CEO, married her husband Muhammad Ali who she met using the website.<ref name="asianimage">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.asianimage.co.uk/news/8677558.How_I_met_my_perfect_match/|title=How I met my perfect match|work= |location= |publisher=''Asian Image''|date=19 November 2010|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref><ref name="ndtv">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/world/dating-services-for-the-modern-muslim-65362|title=Dating services for the modern Muslim|work= |location= |publisher=''[[NDTV]]''|date=9 November 2010|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

In March 2012, Rashid Khan and Damon Scully, who appeared on [[Channel 4]] documentary series ''[[Make Bradford British]]'', endorsed the website.<ref name="youtube">{{cite web |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=syieBbJPTRo|title="Is Damon a Muslim?" (from Make Bradford British)|publisher=SingleMuslim.com|date=28 March 2012|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

